>> I remember going to
a conference in the UK.

00:54:28.790 --> 00:54:31.160 align:middle line:10%
I think that was 2003.

00:54:31.160 --> 00:54:32.810 align:middle line:10%
Yeah, 2003, I think it was.

00:54:32.810 --> 00:54:35.030 align:middle line:84%
And I said, I'm
doing my PhD while I

00:54:35.030 --> 00:54:36.740 align:middle line:90%
sleep in my lucid dreams.

00:54:36.740 --> 00:54:38.600 align:middle line:84%
That's where I'm doing
my research, which

00:54:38.600 --> 00:54:41.390 align:middle line:90%
is a bit preposterous to hear.

00:54:41.390 --> 00:54:42.440 align:middle line:90%
But it was true.

00:54:42.440 --> 00:54:44.390 align:middle line:84%
But people in the
audience were like, what

00:54:44.390 --> 00:54:46.520 align:middle line:84%
are you saying, how
could that be possible,

00:54:46.520 --> 00:54:49.710 align:middle line:84%
and lucid dreaming doesn't
really exist, and all of this.

00:54:49.710 --> 00:54:52.100 align:middle line:84%
And so then I gave them
the scientific facts.

00:54:52.100 --> 00:54:53.870 align:middle line:84%
And some people as
well in that audience

00:54:53.870 --> 00:54:56.990 align:middle line:84%
came up to me afterwards and
said, I'm a psychoanalyst

00:54:56.990 --> 00:54:59.580 align:middle line:84%
and I have worked for
30 years with dreams

00:54:59.580 --> 00:55:02.060 align:middle line:84%
and I've never heard
about lucid dreaming.

00:55:02.060 --> 00:55:04.160 align:middle line:84%
And I think it could
really help my clients.

00:55:04.160 --> 00:55:06.650 align:middle line:10%
>> In the 1960s, there was a
lot of research going on with

00:55:06.650 --> 00:55:07.700 align:middle line:10%
psychedelics.

00:55:07.700 --> 00:55:10.370 align:middle line:10%
Well, that got pushed
underground very quickly

00:55:10.370 --> 00:55:11.540 align:middle line:10%
and it became illegal.

00:55:11.540 --> 00:55:14.030 align:middle line:10%
That is rising very
quickly as well.

00:55:14.030 --> 00:55:15.920 align:middle line:84%
Because the moment you
start doing research

00:55:15.920 --> 00:55:18.320 align:middle line:84%
on something as dramatic as
a psychedelic experience,

00:55:18.320 --> 00:55:22.970 align:middle line:84%
you realize that there's a whole
bunch of very useful things

00:55:22.970 --> 00:55:24.560 align:middle line:90%
that you can do in those states.

00:55:24.560 --> 00:55:26.510 align:middle line:84%
People who have a
terminal illness

00:55:26.510 --> 00:55:29.810 align:middle line:84%
and are facing enormous amounts
of fear and angst over it,

00:55:29.810 --> 00:55:32.270 align:middle line:84%
they can have a psychedelic
experience, which gives them

00:55:32.270 --> 00:55:35.950 align:middle line:84%
a mystical experience, and
their fear of death vanishes.

00:55:35.950 --> 00:55:39.310 align:middle line:84%
They will say then, not only
terminally ill patients,

00:55:39.310 --> 00:55:41.710 align:middle line:84%
but other people will say
that the experience they

00:55:41.710 --> 00:55:45.370 align:middle line:84%
have under the right conditions
with something like psilocybin

00:55:45.370 --> 00:55:49.250 align:middle line:84%
is the most profound experience
in their entire life.

00:55:49.250 --> 00:55:51.560 align:middle line:90%
Well, that's pretty good.

00:55:51.560 --> 00:55:55.790 align:middle line:84%
So it's quite different than
the chaos that was surrounding

00:55:55.790 --> 00:55:57.230 align:middle line:90%
psychedelics in the '60s.

00:55:57.230 --> 00:56:00.500 align:middle line:84%
It's more mature
now, more controlled.

00:56:00.500 --> 00:56:04.760 align:middle line:84%
But it's an example of where
aspects of consciousness that

00:56:04.760 --> 00:56:07.880 align:middle line:84%
are normally pushed aside,
as like the only thing

00:56:07.880 --> 00:56:10.400 align:middle line:84%
you should pay attention to
is the here and now, well,

00:56:10.400 --> 00:56:12.600 align:middle line:84%
that's a very small
slice of reality.

00:56:12.600 --> 00:56:15.170 align:middle line:10%
>> There's a lot of important
issues and we each just have

00:56:15.170 --> 00:56:17.980 align:middle line:10%
our piece of the puzzle.

00:56:17.980 --> 00:56:19.680 align:middle line:10%
But the more we can
understand and know

00:56:19.680 --> 00:56:21.720 align:middle line:10%
what our piece of the
puzzle is and do that

00:56:21.720 --> 00:56:25.590 align:middle line:10%
without the resistance that
comes from being told that what

00:56:25.590 --> 00:56:27.870 align:middle line:10%
we want to do is
wrong, then I think

00:56:27.870 --> 00:56:30.840 align:middle line:10%
we can really, collectively,
make a huge difference.

00:56:30.840 --> 00:56:34.290 align:middle line:10%
>> In the academic world, you
can study these phenomena from

00:56:34.290 --> 00:56:36.150 align:middle line:10%
the point of view
of anthropology,

00:56:36.150 --> 00:56:39.700 align:middle line:10%
certainly from psychology in
terms of belief and what people

00:56:39.700 --> 00:56:40.500 align:middle line:10%
experience.

00:56:40.500 --> 00:56:42.520 align:middle line:84%
But from a scientific
perspective,

00:56:42.520 --> 00:56:44.880 align:middle line:84%
it's very, very rare
to find anywhere

00:56:44.880 --> 00:56:47.790 align:middle line:84%
in the world which is
using scientific approaches

00:56:47.790 --> 00:56:49.260 align:middle line:84%
to studying these
phenomena, even

00:56:49.260 --> 00:56:51.810 align:middle line:84%
though most people actually
have these experiences.

00:56:51.810 --> 00:56:54.180 align:middle line:84%
It's a very strange taboo,
but it's quite strong.

00:56:54.180 --> 00:56:57.240 align:middle line:10%
>> Someone would say, well,
you're now assuming that mental

00:56:57.240 --> 00:56:59.520 align:middle line:10%
things are somehow different
than physical things.

00:56:59.520 --> 00:57:02.100 align:middle line:10%
And mental things
behave differently

00:57:02.100 --> 00:57:04.230 align:middle line:10%
than the rules we expect
for physical things

00:57:04.230 --> 00:57:05.940 align:middle line:10%
where causality
is a certain way.

00:57:05.940 --> 00:57:07.573 align:middle line:90%
That's a common discussion.

00:57:07.573 --> 00:57:09.240 align:middle line:84%
And I say, yeah, so
what's your evidence

00:57:09.240 --> 00:57:11.615 align:middle line:84%
that mental things aren't
different from physical things?

00:57:11.615 --> 00:57:13.770 align:middle line:84%
They sure seem
different in every way.

00:57:13.770 --> 00:57:17.800 align:middle line:84%
Having a thought sure seems like
something that isn't physical.

00:57:17.800 --> 00:57:20.410 align:middle line:10%
It doesn't have any physical
properties like location.

00:57:20.410 --> 00:57:23.770 align:middle line:84%
The thought of the color green
has no location, has no mass,

00:57:23.770 --> 00:57:28.480 align:middle line:84%
it has no frequency, no
spin, no phase, no charge.

00:57:28.480 --> 00:57:31.600 align:middle line:84%
How is it in any way like
anything else that's physical?

00:57:31.600 --> 00:57:34.150 align:middle line:84%
They'll say, then
that's dualism--

00:57:34.150 --> 00:57:36.262 align:middle line:90%
which is just a bludgeon.

00:57:36.262 --> 00:57:37.720 align:middle line:84%
And I say, of
course, it's dualism.

00:57:37.720 --> 00:57:39.010 align:middle line:84%
I'm saying mental
and physical things

00:57:39.010 --> 00:57:40.052 align:middle line:90%
are two different things.

00:57:40.052 --> 00:57:41.538 align:middle line:90%
That's two, that's dualism.

00:57:41.538 --> 00:57:42.580 align:middle line:90%
And then there's nothing.

00:57:42.580 --> 00:57:43.600 align:middle line:90%
There's no argument.

00:57:43.600 --> 00:57:46.060 align:middle line:84%
So the argument is
just, you can't possibly

00:57:46.060 --> 00:57:48.880 align:middle line:84%
be a dualist because
that's not allowed

00:57:48.880 --> 00:57:52.752 align:middle line:84%
in the world of
science, you see.

00:57:52.752 --> 00:57:54.460 align:middle line:84%
Because mental things
don't really exist,

00:57:54.460 --> 00:57:56.080 align:middle line:90%
but physical things do.

00:57:56.080 --> 00:58:01.150 align:middle line:84%
And the history of that has
a lot to do with behaviorism.

00:58:01.150 --> 00:58:02.650 align:middle line:84%
At least in psychology,
it has a lot

00:58:02.650 --> 00:58:04.180 align:middle line:84%
to do with behaviorism
coming out.

00:58:04.180 --> 00:58:05.770 align:middle line:84%
Behaviorism was all
about, we're going

00:58:05.770 --> 00:58:07.810 align:middle line:84%
to figure out what's going
on in people's minds, which

00:58:07.810 --> 00:58:10.210 align:middle line:84%
don't really exist, by looking
at the input and output

00:58:10.210 --> 00:58:12.100 align:middle line:84%
relationships because
that's what we can see.

00:58:12.100 --> 00:58:14.140 align:middle line:90%
What if we actually went inside?

00:58:14.140 --> 00:58:16.990 align:middle line:84%
The thing about mental things
rather than physical things

00:58:16.990 --> 00:58:19.480 align:middle line:84%
is you can actually
go inside experiences

00:58:19.480 --> 00:58:21.340 align:middle line:84%
because you're
having an experience

00:58:21.340 --> 00:58:23.200 align:middle line:90%
and you can discover things.

00:58:23.200 --> 00:58:25.360 align:middle line:84%
That's a different--
that's a different tool.

00:58:25.360 --> 00:58:27.400 align:middle line:84%
But it's still a
scientific tool.

00:58:27.400 --> 00:58:30.010 align:middle line:84%
>> Students, especially, they
would love to study psychic

00:58:30.010 --> 00:58:31.450 align:middle line:90%
phenomena.

00:58:31.450 --> 00:58:33.562 align:middle line:84%
And yet you don't see it
in the academic world.

00:58:33.562 --> 00:58:35.020 align:middle line:84%
We're talking about
administrators.

00:58:35.020 --> 00:58:36.850 align:middle line:10%
We're talking about
senior professors.

00:58:36.850 --> 00:58:38.770 align:middle line:10%
We're talking about
people who hold

00:58:38.770 --> 00:58:43.330 align:middle line:10%
what amounts to the acceptable
topics to talk about.

00:58:43.330 --> 00:58:48.220 align:middle line:84%
>> There's a fear, often, that
can constrain you in academia.

00:58:48.220 --> 00:58:51.400 align:middle line:84%
The underlying fear is the
fear of being shamed for not

00:58:51.400 --> 00:58:53.503 align:middle line:90%
being right, for being a fool.

00:58:53.503 --> 00:58:54.670 align:middle line:90%
You don't want to be a fool.

00:58:54.670 --> 00:58:55.780 align:middle line:84%
The whole point of
academia is, we're

00:58:55.780 --> 00:58:57.548 align:middle line:84%
going to figure out
what's really going on

00:58:57.548 --> 00:58:59.090 align:middle line:84%
and we're going to
be right about it.

00:58:59.090 --> 00:59:00.590 align:middle line:84%
And if you don't
understand this,

00:59:00.590 --> 00:59:02.040 align:middle line:84%
you don't really understand
what's really going on.

00:59:02.040 --> 00:59:03.010 align:middle line:90%
You're a fool.

00:59:03.010 --> 00:59:05.110 align:middle line:84%
You don't want to be on
the outside of the cult.

00:59:05.110 --> 00:59:07.900 align:middle line:84%
>> The university administrator
just does not want anything bad

00:59:07.900 --> 00:59:09.100 align:middle line:90%
to happen ever.

00:59:09.100 --> 00:59:11.080 align:middle line:84%
So they're more afraid
of being embarrassed

00:59:11.080 --> 00:59:12.370 align:middle line:90%
than they are of dying.

00:59:12.370 --> 00:59:15.328 align:middle line:84%
And they don't want to have
to explain to somebody,

00:59:15.328 --> 00:59:16.870 align:middle line:84%
oh, yeah, we have
in this department,

00:59:16.870 --> 00:59:18.610 align:middle line:90%
we're studying this weird stuff.

00:59:18.610 --> 00:59:21.280 align:middle line:84%
They just say, no, we're
not doing anything weird.

00:59:21.280 --> 00:59:23.410 align:middle line:90%
We're completely normal.

00:59:23.410 --> 00:59:27.100 align:middle line:84%
That's the administrator
mindset, which I understand.

00:59:27.100 --> 00:59:30.652 align:middle line:84%
Only unusual places, unusual
universities or institutes

00:59:30.652 --> 00:59:33.110 align:middle line:84%
like ours where we say, well,
we don't care what you think.

00:59:33.110 --> 00:59:34.670 align:middle line:84%
This is what we're doing
because we think it's

00:59:34.670 --> 00:59:35.990 align:middle line:90%
an interesting thing to do.

00:59:35.990 --> 00:59:38.400 align:middle line:84%
>> See, at PEAR, we
were very fortunate.

00:59:38.400 --> 00:59:40.910 align:middle line:84%
We had an
interdisciplinary staff.

00:59:40.910 --> 00:59:44.570 align:middle line:84%
We had physicists, and
psychologists, and engineers.

00:59:44.570 --> 00:59:46.730 align:middle line:10%
All of these people
working together

00:59:46.730 --> 00:59:48.920 align:middle line:10%
on a topic that had no answers.

00:59:48.920 --> 00:59:50.930 align:middle line:10%
We didn't even
know the questions.

00:59:50.930 --> 00:59:54.200 align:middle line:10%
But we did find that when
we put our heads together,

00:59:54.200 --> 00:59:58.250 align:middle line:10%
each of us coming from our
own unique point of view,

00:59:58.250 --> 01:00:02.030 align:middle line:10%
we were discovering things that
we never would have seen alone.

01:00:02.030 --> 01:00:04.115 align:middle line:84%
>> If you look back,
maybe 30 years ago,

01:00:04.115 --> 01:00:05.990 align:middle line:84%
and you were trying to
find conferences to go

01:00:05.990 --> 01:00:09.170 align:middle line:84%
to on consciousness, it would
have been very, very difficult.

01:00:09.170 --> 01:00:12.650 align:middle line:84%
Both in the public domain
and in the academic domains,

01:00:12.650 --> 01:00:14.210 align:middle line:90%
they didn't happen.

01:00:14.210 --> 01:00:16.552 align:middle line:90%
Now we're saturated with them.

01:00:16.552 --> 01:00:18.260 align:middle line:84%
There are conferences
all over the place,

01:00:18.260 --> 01:00:19.820 align:middle line:84%
around the world
on consciousness

01:00:19.820 --> 01:00:21.080 align:middle line:90%
and aspects of consciousness.

01:00:21.080 --> 01:00:23.450 align:middle line:84%
And it includes philosophy
and science and neuroscience

01:00:23.450 --> 01:00:27.300 align:middle line:84%
and everything else, but they're
there and they're very popular.

01:00:27.300 --> 01:00:28.770 align:middle line:90%
There are journals based on it.

01:00:28.770 --> 01:00:30.870 align:middle line:84%
There are centers
at universities now.

01:00:30.870 --> 01:00:32.660 align:middle line:84%
So that has
significantly changed.

01:00:32.660 --> 01:00:34.830 align:middle line:84%
It's hard to see the
change if it's slow.

01:00:34.830 --> 01:00:37.520 align:middle line:90%
It's a 30-year cycling up.

01:00:37.520 --> 01:00:39.590 align:middle line:90%
But that's likely to remain.

01:00:39.590 --> 01:00:42.800 align:middle line:84%
>> To me, I'm all about, let's
change the culture that look

01:00:42.800 --> 01:00:44.630 align:middle line:90%
at it as some problem.

01:00:44.630 --> 01:00:46.230 align:middle line:84%
Instead get out
there, like, look,

01:00:46.230 --> 01:00:47.900 align:middle line:84%
this is scientifically
validated.

01:00:47.900 --> 01:00:50.330 align:middle line:84%
It's a small effect on average,
some people are talented.

01:00:50.330 --> 01:00:53.150 align:middle line:84%
But almost anyone can improve
their abilities to the extent

01:00:53.150 --> 01:00:55.350 align:middle line:84%
that we can develop
this as humanity

01:00:55.350 --> 01:00:57.540 align:middle line:84%
and get more
operational about it.

01:00:57.540 --> 01:01:01.880 align:middle line:84%
We could actually shift our
understanding of the future

01:01:01.880 --> 01:01:04.290 align:middle line:84%
and navigate the future
more effectively.

01:01:04.290 --> 01:01:08.066 align:middle line:84%
So given that, how are you
going to use it for good?

